:"1259","1215":"1215","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","about 1259":"circa 1259","Bef 1298":"vóór 1298","1298":"1298","1339":"1339","Blackborough, Devon, England":"Blackborough, Devon, England","Cooling, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Cooling, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Cobham, Kent, England":"Cobham, Kent, England"},"en":{"1241–Bef 1298":"1241–before 1298","1241–1298":"1241–1298","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1260–1339":"1260–1339","1262–1335":"1262–1335","1215–1250":"1215–1250","–1249":"–1249","about 1260":"about 1260","Aft 1249":"after 1249","1241":"1241","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","3 January 1250":"3 January 1250","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","about 1259":"about 1259","Bef 1298":"before 1298","1298":"1298","1339":"1339","Blackborough, Devon, England":"Blackborough, Devon, England","Cooling, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Cooling, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Cobham, Kent, England":"Cobham, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":18,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":49,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Septvans was born in 1241, in Kent, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sir Robert Septvans, Knight and Matilda. She married John de Cobham about 1259, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died before 1298, and was buried in Cobham, Kent, England."},"et":{"1241–Bef 1298":"1241–enne 1298","1241–1298":"1241–1298","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1260–1339":"1260–1339","1262–1335":"1262–1335","1215–1250":"1215–1250","–1249":"–1249","about 1260":"umbes 1260","Aft 1249":"pärast 1249","1241":"1241","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","3 January 1250":"3. jaanuar 1250","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1259":"1259",